{"title": "Crisis: A Record of the Darker Races, Vol. I, No. 3", "description": "The Crisis is the official publication of the NAACP first published in 1910 with W. E. B. Du Bois, one of the founders, as editor. He exercised almost total control of the content and opinions of the publication until he resigned in 1934. Du Bois was one of the most ardent advocates for total civil rights for all racial minorities and was a prolific author for the cause.\r\nFrom Du Bois\u2019 editorial: \u201cThe object of this publication is to set forth those facts and arguments which show the danger of race prejudice, particularly as manifested to-day toward colored people. It takes its name from the fact that the editors believe that this is a critical time in the history of the advancement of men.\u201d  This issue has editorials, opinions, and articles such as \"An Appeal to Europe,\" Employment of Colored Women in Chicago,\" and special articles, \"The Teacher,\" by Leslie Pinckney Hill, and, \"Social Control\" by Jane Addams.\r\n - Summary by Larry Wilson", "duration": 9962, "language": "English", "authors": [{"id": "1655", "name": "W. E. B. Du Bois"}], "coverArt": "https://archive.org/download/crisisarecordofthedarkerraces3_2406_librivox/crisisv1n3_2406.jpg", "copyright_year": "1910", "genres": ["Essays & Short Works", "Social Science (Culture & Anthropology)"], "supporters": [{"role": "Read by", "name": "LibriVox Volunteers"}, {"role": "Book Coordinator", "name": "Larry Wilson"}, {"role": "Meta Coordinator", "name": "Lynne T"}, {"role": "Proof Listener", "name": "mleigh"}], "sections": [{"section": 1, "title": "Object and Mission, Committee Members,  Advertisements", "readers": [8425], "path": "https://www.archive.org/download/crisisarecordofthedarkerraces3_2406_librivox/crisisvol1no3_01_dubois_64kb.mp3", "duration": 339}, {"section": 2, "title": "Along the Colored Line: Political, The Courts, Social Uplift", "readers": [12385], "path": "https://www.archive.org/download/crisis